wrote:

> *@kennknowles* commented on this pull request.
> ------------------------------
>
> In sdks/java/core/src/main/java/org/apache/beam/sdk/io/FileBasedSink.java
> <https://github.com/apache/beam/pull/2212#discussion_r106963759>:
>
> > +  public abstract static class FilenamePolicy
> +      implements org.apache.beam.sdk.transforms.SerializableFunction<
> +       FilenamePolicy.Context, String> {
> +    /**
> +     * Context used for generating a name based on window, pane, shard numer, and num shards.
> +     * Window and pane will only be provided if windowed writes have been requested using
> +     * {@link Write.Bound#withWindowedWrites}. The policy must produce unique filenames for unique
> +     * Context objects.
> +     */
> +    public static class Context {
> +      @Nullable private BoundedWindow window;
> +      @Nullable private PaneInfo paneInfo;
> +      private int shardNumber;
> +      private int numShards;
> +
> +      public Context(
>
> The implication of a Context parameter is that it is just an optional
> bunch of bits that you could use or not based on your logic. The whole
> point of the Context design pattern is to add and change parameters
> without the user having to adjust their class, while the same user code
> would be executed.
>
> But that's the opposite of what we want - if you ignore any provided piece
> of info, you are likely to be clobbering other data. We actually want any
> new or changed parameters to be a new code path that is unsupported until
> the user gets around to implementing it.
>
> So the API for right now should reflect these properties:
>
>    - there are just two cases
>    - in both cases you really need to use all the information
>    - you should know at construction time whether the policy supports the
>    case you need
>
> Something like:
>
> abstract class FileNamePolicy implements Serializable {
>
>   abstract String filenameForGlobalData(int shardNum, int numShards);
>
>   String filenameForWindowedData(
>       int shardNum, int numShards, BoundedWindow w, PaneInfo paneInfo) {
>     throw new UnsupportedOperationException(
>         "This filename policy cannot be used with windowed input");
>   }
>
>   // And maybe this
>   abstract boolean verifySupportsWindowedOutput;
> }
>
> This could conceivably be factored into some base classes named for what
> they support, or even separate abstract classes, either of which could be
> provided to FileBasedSink, to make the distinction easy to detect.
>
> It would be best to actually detect whether it supports windowing or not,
> but I don't know if we have the bandwidth to get something together along
> those lines.
>
